This paper is about implementing spiking neural networks on FPGA, which falls under the category of hardware design and optimization for neural networks. The paper also discusses the use of probabilistic interpretation of weights to reduce memory accesses and updates, which is related to the field of probabilistic machine learning (cs.LG). The benchmark networks used in the study are related to image recognition tasks, which falls under the category of computer vision (cs.CV). The paper also discusses the trade-offs in accuracy for fully connected and convolutional networks, which is related to the field of neural network architecture design (cs.NE). Finally, the paper discusses the effects of introducing randomness into the spike processing, which is related to the field of neuromorphic engineering (cs.ET) and the use of stochastic processes in neural networks (cs.AR).
